column169: package was found in van leaking white substance. Package was placed in a hazmat tote. upon inspection bottom of the plastic drum had a crack causing an internal leakage.

On 5/8/24 at approximately 1130, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 294822 at the hub facility in Anchorage, reporting a dangerous goods spill.  The shipment consists two plastic jerricans, individually overpacked into fiberboard boxes.  One of the shipments appeared to have a loose closure, resoulting in spillage from the top.  The damaged drum was placed in a salvage drum and the entire shipment is being held, awaiting an amended shipper's declaration for further transport.

Clean Harbors was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 2ft-by-2ft area of the trailer floor and a 5ft-by-10ft area of the concrete lot and estimated that twenty (20) pounds of material was released due to improper loading that punctured four (4) 50-pound plastic bags. Clean Harbors personnel moved all the plastic bags from the pallet to verify only four (4) bags were damaged and then swept up the released material. The damaged bags and recovered material were placed into two (2) 55-gallon poly drums and was staged onsite at the terminal prior to the contractor demobilization. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

column169: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While reversing into dock area at PepsiCo facility, vehicle struck another truck in lot, which damaged the saddle tank. Approximately 20 gallons of Diesel fuel were released to the asphalt surface and a minimal amount migrated to the nearby storm drain. PepsiCo personnel contained the release, and ACT Environmental was dispatched to perform the cleanup. Upon arrival on site, ACT Environmental applied absorbent material to the affected asphalt and inspected the nearby storm drain. Absorbent pads were utilized within storm drain catch basin to soak free product, and no further residual remained. Product was contained to the storm drain catch basin and did not migrate through drainage system. All spent absorbent material and pads were recovered and containerized into one 55-gallon drum, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations. There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column170: PBNA maintains and will continue to administer its robust professional driver program, which aims at driver safety and the reduction of vehicle incidents.

column169: Driver finished C02 customer fill process. While fill hose was being retracted on hose reel, it unexpectedly contacted the vapor ball valve and it inadvertently opened causing Carbon Dioxide to vent out of the delivery vehicle. Driver could not visually locate vapor ball valve due to carbon dioxide cloud. Driver's supervisor instructed driver to move vehicle to open area so cloud could dissipate. Local fire department was contacted by witness. Fire department showed up on scene and assisted with closing vapor ball valve which stopped the uncontrolled release of carbon dioxide. The total event took approximately 40 minutes.

On 5/19/24, we received notification from hub personnel that a foul odor was emitting from ISO tank SUTU 266444. The tank was labeled with the commodity "POLYSULFIDE 9. MARINE POLLUTANT" (UN 3082, HAZMAT), prompting to call out an environmental contractor     United Pumping to assess the incident. The responder discovered several loose bolts on the top manway hatch. The product inside the tank appeared to be stable, with no residue or spillover on the top area of the tank. It seems the loose bolts found on the top hatch cover allowed vapor to escape, causing the foul odor. After tightening the bolts, the odor dissipated over some time. The seals on the top hatch remained intact and undamaged.
column170: Shipper should review incident to determine root cause and corrective measures.

column169: Shipper alerted TOTE that they had 3 road tankers sail on voyage 24077 with undeclared HAZ. At this time the vessel was underway in the Gulf of Alaska. Their Heavy Haul division reports that these last contained with methanol, and should have placards. Here are the trailer numbers and bookings: T 8030- SEA001024040 T 8014- SEA001024041 T 53009- SEA001024043
column170: Internally when a booking doesn't have hazardous the booking is updated by another department. TOTE is looking to change an internal process for checking these to confirm they have been cleaned and purge.

Upon arrival at the destination terminal, the drum was discovered to be leaking on the linehaul trailer. Investigation revealed that the drum may have been punctured by a protruding nail or screw in the trailer roll door. The puncture was very small and at the top of the drum so only a small amount of material was released. When stationary, the drum was not leaking. The drum was set aside awaiting disposition from the shipper.
column170: This incident may have been prevented had the drum been loaded farther away from the rear trailer roll door. Possibly better blocking and bracing may have prevented this minor puncture from occurring. This incident may be used in future dock meeting training topics to illustrate the importance of proper loading techniques.

column169: On 05-12-2024 a CN transportation employee observed liquid dripping from the bottom outlet valve cap during routine work operations at the CN Geismar Yard in Geismar, LA. The employee notified the on-duty transportation manager who then initiated an emergency response from the CN Dangerous Goods Team.  The responding CN DGO observed liquid dripping from the Bottom Outlet Valve cap (attached) with a strong vinegar type odor in the area. It was also noted that the valve handle was found to be in the fully closed position with a shipper supplied security seal intact. The bottom outlet valve cap was checked for tightness with a pipe wrench and was found to be loose (easily able to turn with a pipe wrench). The bottom outlet valve did not create a liquid tight seal while in the closed position in conjunction with an improperly tightened securement cap allowed the contents to leak out onto the ground.  The rail car has a faulty bottom outlet valve and will be transloaded in a shipper provided rail car. The leaking rail car will require an OTMA 1 to move to home shop for a qualified inspection and repair/requalification.

column169: NS personnel inside Brosnan Yard (Macon, GA) reported a Chlorine release from an unidentified car. A personnel reported a strong smell of Chlorine while walking the line of tank cars.  Upon inspection by a contractor, it was noted that tank car OLNX 711120 was the car that was leaking. A strong smell of chlorine was noted, audible hissing was found, degradation to the paint in the protective housing was noted.  The source of the leak was found to be the Tell-Tale valve on the PRD. The valve was open.  The tell-tale valve was closed and the leak stopped. The tell-tale valve leaking also indicates the rupture disc under the PRD was not intact.

column169: The CTMV was travelling northeast on NC 222.  The truck drove off the right side of the roadway, overcorrected, and then skidded across the center line and overturned onto its side. The cost for the cleanup and remediation is still pending final notification from the contractor.

Crew was switching the north bound road train out at Riker yard.  The conductor spotted railcar UTLX 211952 was leaking product out of the top of the car.  The conductor stopped the move and called BPRR Management.  After investigating the manway seal on the top of the rail car it was found to be defective and allowed product to come out.  No product was on the ground - only on the side of the car.  Crew wiped down side of rail car with absorbent pads and disposed of properly.  Notification was made to Rita Mager, Environmental Director.  MEI came to Riker yard and made repairs on the car.  MEI Report, B&P Spill Report, Photos attached; also available upon request to rita.mager@gwrr.com
column170: Shipper should keep a maintenance record on rail car and items that were found to be defective and replaced.  Analyze data to find the average life span of gaskets and seals.

column63: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column169: UTLX 208792 had a slow drip of diesel from the BOV cap. After inspecting found the BOV had a disengaging bottom outlet handle. The handle was disengaged and secured with the BOV not completely closed and securement pin hanging from chain. Outlet cap was found slightly tool tight but able to be easily turned with wrench. Bottom outlet cap was removed, and cap gasket inspected found to be in good condition. No product dripping from the BOV after completely closing the valve BO/cap reinstalled, and tool tightened.
column170: Properly secure tank car before releasing from plant. Inspecting the BOV to ensure the valve is completely closed and installing the securement pin at the valve stem ears, before disengaging the handle. Install the bottom outlet cap and tool tightening as a secondary leak control as designed.

column169: Halfway through the flight, passenger 20A, told FA Pang that their laptop was emitting an electrical smell. FA conferred with FM and both agreed there was a smell. No flames, heat, or smoke were present. Out of an abundance of caution, the MacBook Pro was placed into the TCB. The TCB was placed in an aft lav and monitored occasionally per CA instructions occasionally throughout the flight. The TCB remained in the aft lav until descent, in which it was brought to the forward lav for easy access upon door opening. Due to no signs of fire, smoke, or heat, pax was escorted to the exit and was able to retrieve the laptop out of the TCB. FAs reminded to fill out IORs and thanked for erring on the side of caution.

R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to remediate the impacted site. CGTX 31156 On 05-06-2024 an FRA Hazardous Materials Safety Inspector performed a regulatory compliance check on tank car CGTX 31156 (Last Contained, Diesel Fuel, UN 1202, Class 3, PG II) at the CN Destrehan Yard in Destrehan, LA. The inspection revealed that (8) of (8) manway cover swing bolts were not properly fastened, the 2" vapor valve was in the fully opened position with it's securement plug not attached, the 3" liquid valve securement plug was not attached. The inspector also noted a diesel type odor upon opening the protective housing. The inspector notified the CN Dangerous Goods Officer of the findings. The CN DGO requested the tank car be placed on an accessible track for further investigation.  The responding CN DGO did not detect any diesel type odor upon opening the protective housing. A (4) gas with PID gas monitor was placed at the opening of the fully opened 2" vapor valve for several minutes. There were no detectable LEL or VOC readings emanating from the open valve or within the protective housing cover. The gas monitor was also placed next to the un-secured manway cover for gas detection purposes. There were no LEL or VOC's detected.  The vapor valve was closed, and its securement plug was applied utilizing a 24" pipe wrench. The liquid valve securement plug was applied utilizing a 24" pipe wrench. The (8) manway cover swing bolts were tightened with a 24" pipe wrench. The placards on the tank car (combustible liquid) were not consistent with the shipping papers (flammable liquid) and were replaced.

column169: Tank truck was being loaded with 45,000 lbs of formaldehyde solution, Toward end of loading, a high level probe should have stopped the pump and prevented overfilling of the tank. When overfilling occurred, the driver recognized it almost immediately and shut down the pump manually. Spilled formaldehyde solution flowed down the side of the truck on to the truck loading pad, and then toward secondary containment ditch to the east of. the pad. The truck and loading pad were washed down with water into the containment ditch where it drained into a sump and was conveyed by in-place submersible pump to a recycle storage tank. Spilage was estimated at 20-to-30 gallons. Investigation found that high level probe was set to trigger 10-seconds after contact w/ solution. It should have been set for a 1-second response

column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED

The incident report was filed due to spillage of Diesel Fuel from the saddle tank from the power unit. The CMV jackknifed causing the  saddle tank to be crush and releasing diesel fuel on the roadway.   The driver failed to maintain control of the CMV and struck a guard rail. The roadway was wet and under construction (repaving) and the surface was uneven. No other vehicles were involved and no injuries were reported.  A local Hazmat clean-up company (ECOtech, 50 Easy Street, London, KY. 40741) responded to the scene. They tapped the fuel tank and transferred the contents to slow/stop the leak. The materials used were hydrocarbon exsorbent pads, absorbent booms, recovery drum, skid steer, and a dump truck for disposal.
column170: The driver of the CMV that was involved in the accident/incident was terminated to help prevent recurrence.  All CDL required drivers are vetted to meet our company policy in regards to at least (1) one year CMV driving experience. The driver is also given a road test by an authorized driver that operates the same type CMV.   The company also provides onboarding and continual courses on our LMS. Courses such as: Driver Safety Training for CNV Drivers Hazardous Materials Incident Reporting Training Air Brake System Training Pre-trip/Post-trip Inspection Training Hazardous Materials Transportation Driver Training. Hazardous Materials General Awareness, Safety and Security Training.  The company also distributes monthly safety newsletters and safety bulletins along with holding quarterly driver meetings. Topics such as Drowsy Driving, Driver Fitness for Duty, and various safety topics are routinely shared with the drivers. We post (3) safety bulletins every month in the driver's area, so they can be reminded of safety topics.

On 05-06-2024 an FRA Hazardous Materials Safety Inspector performed a regulatory compliance check on tank car CGTX 31156 (Last Contained, Diesel Fuel, UN 1202, Class 3, PG II) at the CN Destrehan Yard in Destrehan, LA. The inspection revealed that (8) of (8) manway cover swing bolts were not properly fastened, the 2" vapor valve was in the fully opened position with it's securement plug not attached, the 3" liquid valve securement plug was not attached. The inspector also noted a diesel type odor upon opening the protective housing. The inspector notified the CN Dangerous Goods Officer of the findings. The CN DGO requested the tank car be placed on an accessible track for further investigation.  The responding CN DGO did not detect any diesel type odor upon opening the protective housing. A (4) gas with PID gas monitor was placed at the opening of the fully opened 2" vapor valve for several minutes. There were no detectable LEL or VOC readings emanating from the open valve or within the protective housing cover. The gas monitor was also placed next to the un-secured manway cover for gas detection purposes. There were no LEL or VOC's detected.  The vapor valve was closed, and its securement plug was applied utilizing a 24" pipe wrench. The liquid valve securement plug was applied utilizing a 24" pipe wrench. The (8) manway cover swing bolts were tightened with a 24" pipe wrench. The placards on the tank car (combustible liquid) were not consistent with the shipping papers (flammable liquid) and were replaced.  CGTX 31181 On 05-06-2024 an FRA Hazardous Materials Safety Inspector performed a regulatory compliance check on tank car CGTX 31181 (Last Contained, Diesel Fuel, UN 1202, Class 3, PG II) at the CN Destrehan Yard in Destrehan, LA. The inspection revealed that the bottom outlet valve cap was less than tool tight (could be turned by hand), (8) of (8) manway cover swing bolts were not properly fastened, the 2" vapor valve was not in the fully closed position with it's securement plug not attached, the 3" liquid valve securement plug was not attached. The inspector also noted a diesel type odor upon opening the protective housing. The inspector notified the CN Dangerous Goods Officer of the findings. The CN DGO requested the tank car be placed on an accessible track for further investigation. The responding CN DGO did not detect any diesel type odor upon opening the protective housing. A (4) gas with PID gas monitor was placed at the opening of the partially open 2" vapor valve for several minutes. There were no detectable LEL or VOC readings emanating from the open valve or within the protective housing cover. The gas monitor was also placed next to the un-secured manway cover for gas detection purposes. There were no LEL or VOC's detected.

Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 50-gallons of product released to a 23' x 8' area of the trailer floor and a 25' x 10' area of the concrete lot below. The release was caused by the tote falling on its side as a result of improper loading. The material was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one. Absorbent and vinegar were deployed and worked into the impacted areas to clean and neutralize the release. The impacted absorbents were containerized into (4) 55-gallon poly drums. The damaged tote was cut up and containerized into a cubic yard box. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column43: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column169: Driver was delivering gasoline to a gas station.  He brought 4000 gallons divided between multiple pockets of his trailer.  Company policy is to not exceed 90% of a tank's capacity, and upon arrival the driver determined the load would be very close to 90%, so he dropped one pocket at a time, sticking the tank before each pocket, and doing the math to ensure each pocket would fit.  Before dropping 1500 gallons from pocket #3, the driver disconnected the delivery hose to stick the tank.  He obtained the inch reading, converted it to gallons, did the required math, and determined the product in the pocket would fit.  He neglected to re-connect the delivery hose before releasing the product.  He realized his mistake immediately, and stopped the flow of product, but in the very short amount of time (just a few seconds, if that) approximately 51 gallons of product was released to the pavement near the fill.     The driver immediately gathered absorbent materials and pads from his spill kit, and did everything he could to contain the release, but product flowed away from the fill, entering a Central Maine Power (CMP) underground electrical vault.  After stopping the release and containing as much as he could, the driver called our company's 24/7 Safety line to report the spill.  The on-call Safety Manager immediately called 911 and was connected to Westbrook Fire who responded.  He then called Green Site Services for cleanup, and ME DEP who also responded.   When it was determined some quantity of gasoline had entered the electrical vault, the fire department evacuated the area and shut down the street until CMP was able to respond.  Ultimately all liquid was vacuumed out of the vault, a confined space team entered and pressure washed the vault, and speedy dry was applied to all surface material, and was subsequently removed and disposed of properly.  ME DEP was present for the clean-up as well, and approved.
column170: This spill was the result of human error.  One simple, but very important step in the process was missed.  Delivery drivers use the same routine repeatedly, and distraction, stress, or many other factors can result in steps being missed.  All drivers, including the one involved in this delivery, will receive re-training with the focus on slowing down, ensuring accuracy and completion of all steps before commencing deliveries.

During inspection for return, the accompanying safety data sheet indicated the shipment was indentified as ID800; however, the package was not prepared in accordance with IATA Regulations, missing the required markings, labels, and paperwork.  Further inspection of the package contents confirmed the classification.  The shipment is being held, pending an investigation by the FAA.

column61: Burst or Ruptured; Burst or Ruptured
column169: Driver was traveling approximately 65 MPH westbound on I-20. He was traveling in the far right lane, when he fell asleep at the wheel. He awoke to stopped traffic in front of him without enough time to come to a safe stop. The driver jerked the wheel to the right to avoid contact with the vehicles in front of him and left the road way. He overturned on a side embankment at MM-43. Upon impact of the crash, a weld in the tank ruptured as well as one of the manhole covers on the top of the trailer. The product slowly leaked out of the trailer for approximately 1 hour. Other vehicles in traffic that witnessed the incident dialed 911. The driver contacted his employer, who in turn contacted Marion Environmental who was closer to the scene and could mitigate the release of gasoline quicker and more efficiently than the carrier could themselves. They set up absorbent booms to control the spilled product. The remainder of the product was pumped over into another trailer and safely transported to the original destination.
column170: The driver who failed to maintain control of his vehicle was immediately terminated from his position at our company. Safety training and reminders were provided to current employees of the company. Spirit Express LLC will continue to provide adequate safety training to its current and future employees.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal UBY experienced a UN1830 Sulfuric Acid  release from 5-gallon poly jugs. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 0.55-gallons of product released to a 5’ x 2’ area of the trailer floor due loose caps on the jugs. The jugs were wiped down, caps were secured, and they were re-stacked and secure for shipment on. Sodium bicarbonate and oil dri were then deployed to clean and neutralize the impacted trailer floor. All impacted absorbents and cleanup debris were then collected and containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

The damaged battery was up righted and secured to a pallet. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

When tank car PROX 44601 was in the WLE Brewster Car Shop for routine repairs, the carmen used a gas detection meter to check the top of the car for leaks after noticing an odor coming from the car.  When they inserted the gas meter inside of the protective housing, the gas meter gave an alarm.  They called myself, John Vergis Environmental Officer for the WLE, to come out and look at the car.  I determined that the Vacuum Relief device was leaking around the O Ring Seal.  I have called the car owner to see how they want to proceed with repairs.  As of 5-29-2024, I have not yet heard back from them.
column170: Use a gas detection meter to check valving when securing cars for transportation.

column169: On 5/14/2024, at 1222 hours, personnel in the CSXT Peach Creek Yard, in Logan, WV, discovered CRDX 14064, a loaded hopper car of Ammonium Nitrate, leaking from the bottom of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, PCS SALES, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2024-0514-00151). SPSI, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the release was due to a partially open slide gate on the bottom of the hopper car.  CSX Mechanical personnel closed the slide gate and SPSI personnel remediated the product release. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative (Amy James, 803-335-9164). The car was released for transportation.

column169: FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED WET IN APPEARANCE BY THE LVD PICK OFF ON THE PD-4. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE TURNED OFF THE POWER AND SECURED THE CONVEYOR BELT, EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN 4 MINUTES A DESIGNATED RESPONDER ARRIVED DONNING THE PROPER PPE AND WITH A FULLY STOCKED SPILL CART. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET THE DAMAGE WAS PH TESTED AND CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 4 POLY 1-GAL JUGS WAS SLIGHTLY LOOSE, CAUSING APPROX. 8 OUNCES OF THE LIQUID PRODUCT TO LEAK THROUGH THE BREACH AND INTO THE BASE OF THE CARTON. THERE WAS NO INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A DOUBLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 51 LBS/IN EDGE CRUSH TEST (ECT).

column169: THE RESPONDER WENT TO THE SPILL, AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL.

On Friday, May 17, 2024, a Occidental Chemical driver made a delivery of Hydrochloric acid to the Occidental Chemical plant located in Hahnville, LA. The Occidental Chemical driver was loaded at an IMTT facility located in Geismar, LA. While the unloading process was underway, it was discovered that the bleeder valve on the product transfer line that goes to the product storage tank was left open. This resulted in approximately 2600 gallons of Hydrochloric acid being released from the product line into the containment area. No injuries or exposure to chemical occurred as a result of this event, as well as no off-site impact or environmental impact. The offloading process was halted, bleeder valve closed, containment area drained to sump for processing, and remainder of offload was completed.
column170: The OxyChem truck driver immediately shut down the offloading operation upon discovery. The area was drained to a treatment sump, washed down and cleaned up. Occidental Chemical Taft Plant as well as Occidental Chemical Private Fleet has launched a joint investigation into this incident. Attendance requirements has been reviewed with all Oxychem drivers.

column169: On 5/6/2024 CPKC Hazmat received notice that a loaded liquid Argon car, MTGX 7050, was observed Ieaking during an inbound train inspection at the Kansas City, MO Knoche yard, and had an iced cabinet. CPKC Hazmat mobilized to the yard along with a railroad qualified response contractor to assist with mitigating the release. Upon arrival, responders found MTGX 7050 to be 85-90% empty. Also, the car needed to be switched into a track where it could be safely secured. Temporary measures were taken to stop the leak utilizing a freeze patch. Hazmat requested the car be isolated in a suitable track for further action. During switching to isolation, the freeze patch failed and after being isolated, the car finished depressurizing. Responders determined the source of the leak was a broken Liquid Sample Valve Feedline(V-13R) in right cabinet, and a loose fitting in the left cabinet on the PB Vapor Recovery Isolation/Check pipe fitting(RCV-1). The total estimated release is 15,336 gallons of liquid Argon(total load loss). The car was on hazmat hold until an OTMA-1 was obtained to move the car to home shop. File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at the time of filing. This shipment was offered as a'bulk' shipment, aka one car load, therefore the exact amount offered in this package is not known to the carrier. This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantify this value.
column170: The Kansas City Southern Railway(KCSR)(DBA CPKC) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases(NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases(a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause Investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCSR.(Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Carl Akins, KCSR Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http:/Mar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

A Veolia employee was moving containers at the 10 day in-transit storage area with a forklift. The employee needed to move the 951H2 overpack container but due to the issues with utilizing certain drum carts to move these, the employee chose to widen the forks and lift the drum utilizing the edges on the container. Upon lifting with the forks, the container slipped from the forks landing on its side. The employee quickly righted the container with the forklift and tightened the closure, but an estimated 1/2 gallon had leaked out. The 95 gallon overpack contained one 55 gallon drum inside.

Driver was delivering Caustic Soda 50% Diaphram to a customer in West Warwick RI on Tuesday morning 5/7/24. Univar Solutions' Driver called dispatch on arrival to customer to report a small release. Driver reported the gasket was pinched on the dome manway which allowed product into the spill box of trailer. Driver backed into the unloading area and noticed a trail of caustic drips leading down the pavement into customer's unloading area. Driver pulled the trailer out of the pitched area to refasten the dome gasket. Driver got the customer's employee to review the release. Customer personnel cleaned up the drips with rags and water. An incident report was filled out and signed by customer.   Further investigation indicated the air valve was open on the trailer and Driver did not conduct a thorough pre trip on the trailer catching the open air valve. The released product at the customer was a result of the open air valve and not the dome gasket.
column170: The driver was retrained on proper pre-trip inspection policies and procedures.

column169: Damaged package left in a tote at NASH 371 HWPA. Inspection found that twelve 32-ounce plastic bottles of Purell Foodservice Surface Sanitizer leaked due to loose caps. This shipment received a DPR, repack and RTS at MEML-386. Repack was shipped without a diamond label or other hazmat markings. No DGNav report or ISF was completed at the time of DPR. The original package also appears to have been undeclared.

On 5/21/24, at 1100 hours, FRA Inspector Vincent Au in the CSXT Manville Yard discovered DNAX 130040, Residue tank car UN1993 Flammable Liquid (Acetone, Toluene) with an improperly placed manway gasket, and a vapor release from the vacuum release device.  The railcar was isolated in yard, and National Response Center and New Jersey Department of Environment were notified, report number 24-05-23-1554-22.  The emergency contact number on the waybill was contacted: 877-818-0087, Velocity Emergency Call Service, with Shipper Contact listed as David Solecki from Veolia Inc.  CSX Manager of Hazardous Materials Graham Clark made contact with David Solecki and informed him of situation.  MEI, a CSX response contractor was dispatched to the scene, and found the improperly placed manway gasket and defective vacuum relief device.  MEI corrected the gasket placement, and removed the vacuum relief device, and put a plug in DNAX 130040.  The plug secured the release, and corrective actions were communicated to David Solecki and FRA Inspector Vincent Au.  The tank car has remained held from transportation pending receipt of an OTMA or further repair by certified repair unit.

column169: HT driver stated that once he hooked up to take his paper work to his tractor when he heard a popping sound. Driver also stated that the when he was opening the external valve the handle felt different and it felt like it was coming out further than it should so he stopped opening  He went  to the back of the trailer and noticed the external valve had came out completely. He then went and hit the emergency valve but product continued to flow out until it finally stopped. HT notified the customer o the spill and the operator returned to the unloading area where he saw the external valve on the ground. HT driver had some product on his clothes and face. He was taken to the hospital for observation. HT driver did not have his hard hat on or face shield at the time

First Call Environmental utilized a drum vacuum to recover the free product from the storm drain catch basin, and confirmed product was contained to catch basin and did not migrate through the sewer system. Two 55-gallon drums of spent absorbent material were generated during the cleanup. There was no impact to soils or threat to state waters. There were no injuries or exposures reported.

A Veolia employee arrived at Veolia's ten day intransit facility to prepare for travel to another office for the week when they noticed a large spill in the warehouse.    The employee determined that the spill was from one 55-1A2 open top metal drum containing "UN1325, Waste Flammable Solids, Organic, n.o.s. (Petroleum Hydrocarbons), 4.1, III, RQ (D001)." The leak was traced to a pinhole puncture in the drum. The poor integrity of the container previously went unnoticed because the puncture did not puncture the exterior paint; a blister had formed and kept the liquid from spilling until the blister ruptured. Approximately 5 gallons of liquid was released until the leak stopped on its own over the weekend and was discovered the following morning.  While the employee moved the drum to be overpacked and was taking pictures of the incident, the drum began to leak again from the same blister.   The employee overpacked the drum, put down oil dry to clean the spill, made sure no other drums were also leaking, and contacted management to inform them of the incident.
column170: It's currently unknown what caused the leak. The drum had no obvious signs of damage on the exterior, and the pinhole seemed to be formed from within the drum. Potential causes could be faults in the drum that were not visible from the exterior, or the waste itself causing the pinholes due to potential contaminants, debris, or other components of the waste material.

column169: On Tuesday, May 22, 2024,a CN mechanical performing an inspection observed that the bottom outlet valve  appeared to be leaking from tank car # UTLX 211004 along with a strong Ethanol type odor in the area. The  employee notified the Transportation Manager who in turn notified the CN Dangerous Goods Team. The tank car  was set out to an isolation track (WA90) for inspection by a CN emergency response contractor.  A CN emergency responsecontractor was dispatched to thelocation for mitigation.Thecontractor performed an  inspection of the tank car and found the bottom outlet valve to be leaking from the threads of the bottom outlet  valve cap. It was determined that there was a failure in the sealing surface of the valve seat to include a defective  gasket. (The BOV cap was found to be less than tool tight and the BOV in the closed position and pinned upon initial  inspection). CN emergency response contractor did observe cable seal to be correctly in place. The BOV cap was  removed and it was observed to be leaking past the closed ball.  The BOV valve handle was cycled several times to the open and closed position to freeany debris that may have  been trapped in the BOV sealing surface potentially causing theleak.The BOV cap was then removed and observed  for 20 minutes to ensurethere was no further leakagefrom thevalve. It was noted that the BOV cap gasket was  deformed and was replaced. The bottom outlet valve cap was then re-installed and tightened with a 36" pipe wrench.  Upon tightening the BOV cap, CN emergency response contractor proceeded to place new cable seals on the BOV /  Cap.

XPO-Logistics contacted ERTS regarding two damaged 55-gallon steel drums containing hazardous product, H.B.  Fuller 14216.One drum was punctured by a forklift and the other was damaged when trying to move it away  from the punctured drum. A Contractor was called to overpack both drums. The Contractor advised that an  estimated 25-gallons of product released onto the wooden trailer floor and the concrete beneath the trailer. The  trailer floor was impacted in a 15’x8.5’ area and the concrete beneath the trailer was impacted in a 10’x 10’ area. The Contractor used oil dry, absorbent pads, and booms to contain and clean-up the release. Two  additional drums of waste were generated for the impacted clean-up debris. No storm-drains, waterways, or  soil were affected by this incident.

column169: Passenger purchased gas generator at a Lowes in New Jersey on 5/27/2024 in an effort to use for disaster relief in Northwest Arkansas. She was under the impression that the unit was new because it was packaged that way and she had no reason to believe otherwise. There were no fumes or noticeable stains on the box. She presented it to the American Airlines ticket counter in PHL for her AA 4602/4342 PHL-LGA-XNA flights operated by Republic Airways, Inc. TSA scanned the item in PHL before being loaded on the aircraft and no dangerous goods were present. Ground crew in PHL loaded it on the aircraft. The unit shipped to LGA and no noticeable spills or fumes were observed by LGA ground crew and the package continued to XNA. Once in XNA ground crew noticed approximately 1 qt leaked on the cargo floor and some luggage. Republic Ops, Maintenance and Dangerous Goods were contacted immediately. On call maintenance contractors for Republic Airways were called out and cleaned the aircraft quickly with several cleaning agents. The extent of gasoline spilled on the cargo floor was minimal.
column170: The FAA PHI for Republic was notified immediately after the Republic DG Manager was made aware. The telephonic NRC report (1400188) was filed on 5/28/2024 at 1822. After getting statements and pictures from AA ops and DG management it was determined the AA ticket counter in PHL followed procedures for accepting the gas generator. No one had any way of knowing the Lowes generator sold to the passenger was, in fact, not used and clearly a returned generator that was resold. I did recommend to AA that perhaps there should be more scrutiny when accepting gas-operated equipment from passengers when trying to check luggage.

Oregon DOT Rail Safety Inspector Christopher Kunzei (FRA Inspector ID H4102) discovered tank car GATX 21575 was venting odor (vapor) during an on-board inspection of the top of the railcar on 05/15/2024.  Inspector Kunzei promptly notified railroad (RVT) train crew, followed by written report (FRA Report H4102-2024-0153).  Railroad train crew stated that they did not smell the odor from the ground during their ground-level inspection at time of shipment acceptance at the Shipper facility.  Amount or duration of odor venting is unknown.  Car had been in transit less than 2 hours (less than 1 mile from Shipper facility).  Railcar was empty (residue) at time of incident, previously contained Methyl Ethyl Ketone (UN 1193, STCC 4909243).  Upon subsequent Shipper re-inspection following the incident, the Shipper determined that the cause of odor venting was due to a damaged (worn) manway gasket.
column170: Suggest that Shipper add inspection of manway gaskets to their railcar shipment inspection procedures, or if already contained therein, provide refresher training on said inspection procedures to Shipper personnel performing said inspections.

column169: On 6/07/2024, the Delta Dangerous Goods management team was notified of an undeclared shipment of 2 non-spillable, wet batteries secured to the back bed of two new golf carts. The golf carts did not contain any fluids (oils, fuels), however, the non-spillable wet batteries were removed/disconnected from the battery compartment and placed/strapped to the aft bed of the cart. There was not a shipping paper associated with the batteries. This event is under immediate investigation.
column170: For awareness purposes, the Delta ATL Cargo team will brief this event and associated risks to personnel during shift briefings. In addition, the ATL Cargo team will produce a bulletin/communication that reminds agents of applicable procedures to prevent undeclared shipments of this nature. This event remains under investigation with likely multiple root causes/corrective actions. I

column169: On Thursday, 05/02/2024, at approximately 5:25am ET. Standard Petroleum's driver was ' traveling on the 1-95 - southbound in the right lane (of3). As Standard Petroleum's driver approached exit 14 on 1-95 southbound, a black Chevy Camaro struck Standard Petroleum's upper right side as the Camaro driver crossed a solid white line when it merged into traffic. After striking Standard Petroleum's vehicle, the Camaro then struck a trailer traveling parallel to Standard Petroleum m the middle lane, which caused the trailer to strike Standard Petroleum's vehicle. The cause of the failure is still being investigated; however, it is Standard Petroleum s understanding that the trailer struck Standard Petroleum's fuel tank which caused a fuel leak. Since the investigation is ongoing, Standard Petroleum is not able to describe the package failure with specificity at this time. ?nee Standard Petroleum's driver discovered the fuel leak, he immediately called 911 and notified Stand ard Petroleum dispatch of the incident. It is Standard Petroleum's unders!anding that either DEEP or Connecticut State Police notified Standard Republic, who is an environmental first responder for the State of Connecticut, to remedy the fuel leak.
column170: Standard Petroleum is actively investigating this matter and reviewing all information received to date to determine appropriate changes and/or adjustments to its operations, training, and/or procedures to help prevent recurrence. To this end, Standard Petroleum anticipates that it will retain National Transportation Consultants to aid in its internal review of Standard Petroleum's existing policies and procedures to help prevent recurrence.

column59: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column169: On May 8, 2024 at 1800 Mechanical personnel in the Conrail Port Reading Yard discovered , HSRX 3130 a loaded tank car of Petroleum Distillates (Isomerate) leaking from the top of the tank car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Kinder Morgan was notified directly via phone . Conrail Manager of  Hazardous Material, Joe Caccamo along with Marion Environmental personnel, investigated the leak and found  the source be from the reclosing pressure relief device. Liquid product was escaping from the PRD indicating an overloaded condition. The magnetic gauging device was completely maxed out and showing no vapor space in the tank car. A vacuum truck was used to safely remove approximately 3500 gallons.  Cause Code: 419 5 x ( 5 + 5 + 0 ) x ( 2+ 0 ) = 100

Driver noticed LNG was Ieaking from the rear cabinet of the MC-338 tanker after he stopped. Bystanders called 911 before the driver could. Farmville Fire Department arrived on scene and would not allow the driver to open the back doors of his transport tanker to determine the source of the leak or to prevent further Ieaking. Farmville FD contacted the state emergency hazmat team and waited for their response. Upon arrival, the state hazmat team noted that the leak had stopped and that there was no danger or threat and allowed the driver to open up the rear doors. The driver ascertained that the leak was coming from a flange to flange connection behind the discharge valve of the transport and waited for a company technician to arrive.
column170: connection that were loose and he got 1/4 tum on each one of the bolts on the flange. The flange connection was secured and the leak was stopped. The MC-338 tanker invoved was a fairly new tanker with less than a few months of service. The thermal expansion and contraction that occurs from designed use Ioosened the bolts just enough to create the small leak. On all new cryogenic tankers received by this company, the bolts on flange to flange connections where LNG will contact and freeze will be checked for the first six months prior to leaving the yard and prior to discharging LNG out of the flange to flange connection.

column169: UPON ARRIVAL AT CONSIGNEE LOCATION OFFLOADING OPERATIONS STARTED. DUE TO A SLIGHT LEAK AT THE EXTERNAL VALVE CONNECTION CONSIGNEE PERSONEL REJECTED LOAD REQUIRING REPAIR AT OFF-SITE LOCATION. DRIVER PROCEEDED TO REPAIR FACILITY FOR ASSISTANCE. AT EVENT LOCATION, CTMV WAS BROUGHT TO DOORWAY OF REPAIR FACILITY DUE TO WEATHER CONDITIONS. DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO ASSIST MECHANICS BY REMOVING EXTERNAL VALVE FROM HOUSING. ONCE VALVE REMOVED FROM PIPE PRODUCT FLOWED FREELY INTO ENVIROMENT. DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO ACTUATE EMERGENCY SHUTOFF. ACTIVATION OF EMERGENCY SHUTOFF FAILED TO STOP FLOW OF PRODUCT. FACILITY EVACUATED DUE TO PRODUCT RELEASE AND INABILITY TO HAULT FLOW FROM TRAILER. VAPOR CLOUD RESULTED FROM PRODUCT FUMES AND WET WEATHER AT TIME OF INCIDENT. DRIVER SUFFERED CHEMICAL BURNS DURING ATTEMPT TO REMOVE VALVE AND HAULT FLOW, WAS TAKEN TO HOSPITAL. INTERNAL INVESTIGATION UNDERWAY CAUSE OF FAILURE AT THIS POINT APPEARS TO BE INTERNAL VALVE SEATING WHICH PREVENTED PROPER OPERATION OF INTERNAL VALVE SEALING VESSEL.  SUPPLIMENTAL REPORT WILL BE FILED WITH ADDITIONAL DETAILS.

The KAG Specialty Products Group, LLC driver arrived at the customer location and was preparing to initiate the delivery. It appears that a valve on the trailer was left in a partially open position. When the driver removed the discharge cap approximately 10 gallons of Bonderite C-IC was released. A portion of the spilled product sprayed on the driver and resulted in him seeking medical treatment. T&R Environmental responded to the scene and handled the remediation.
column170: KAG Specialty Products Group, LLC will inspect the trailer and make sure any necessary repairs are completed.

column169: On May 29th, 2024, Sterling Airways accepted cargo to be moved from ANC to DUT(AWB 359-10000196). When accepting the shipment the ANC based employee asked the shipper if there was any dangerous goods in the shipment. The shipper stated that the package did not contain any dangerous goods. Based on this information, the shipment was accepted by Sterling and placed in storage until the next available flight to DUT. On May 30th, 2024, this shipment was transported on VC1101 to DUT around 8:30am. The next day, as part of the Manager of Ground Operations Standards normal processes, she reviewed the airway bill and discovered that there was a laptop in the description section of the airway bill. All airway bills currently are reviewed no later than the next day by Manager A. The review process of all airway bills was put into place due to cargo being a new process to the airline. The continued monitoring of airway bills is to ensure everything is done correctly. When the Manager of Ground Operations Standards discovered the laptop in the description section, she notified the Anchorage Station Manager of this discovery. The Station Manager then contacted the agent who was involved in creating this airway bill, and verified that there was in fact a laptop transported. Both the Manager of Ground Operations Standards and the Anchorage Station Manager verified that this should not have been transported due to the possibility of a lithium battery in the laptop, as described in section 1.2.C in the Cargo Acceptance Handbook which prohibits transport of lithium batteries. This event was immediately brought to the leadership's attention and notification was sent out to all managers and cargo agents and an investigation was opened.
column170: Based on Sterling's internal SMS process, the following enhancements have been made or are in the process of being implemented: 1. Provide immediate coaching to the employee who made the mistake. 2. Notify and educate all personnel who handle cargo to explain the error that was made and bring awareness. 3. Update the training to include more specifics on items that include lithium batteries. 4. Revise the monitoring system to ensure that the airway bills are reviewed prior to shipment. 5. Revise the airway bill to include a reminder of specific items such as laptops. 6. Add verbiage to the Limited Cargo Acceptance Handbook(LCAH) to outline the procedure for screening cargo shipments for DG. For instance, asking the same questions as are listed in the CSM, Section 5.4

column169: During offloading of the flight a mobility aid scooter arced with a flash and smoke when placed on the cargoveyor outside the aircraft cargo compartment. Upon opening of the battery compartment for the lithium ion battery, it was discovered that it was not the battery but one of the wires in the wire bundle had been pinched in the 2 halves of the battery housing leading to abrasion and a short circuit of the wire. There was some soot and evidence of burning where the wire came into contact with the metal frame of the scooter. There was no thermal runaway of the lithium ion battery although there could have been had the short continued.
column170: Better design/quality control of scooter manufacture.

column169: On 5/19/2024 at approximately 1845, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 906768 at the ramp facilty in Denver, reporting an undeclared dangerous goods commodity.  The shipment consisted of one sealed lead acid battery, packaged in a fiberboard box.  The shipment was discovered showing evidence of spillage. The acid spilled from the battery, however the cause of the spillage is unknown. One employee was reported burned from the acid spillage and was treated with first aid.  It does not appear that the commodity was properly identified nor declared as a sealed lead acid battery.  The shipment is being held, pending an FAA investigation.
